ened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b>, Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’, from <i>breitheamh</i> ‘judge’. Compare   Braham   2."]},{"name":"Bream","meanings":["English:","nickname for a fierce or energetic person, from Middle English <i>brem(e)</i>, <i>brim(me)</i> ‘fierce, vigorous’ (from Old English <i>brēme</i> ‘famous, noble’), or from a Middle English form of the Old English personal name <i>Brēme</i> with the same meaning.","variant of   Braham  ."]},{"name":"Brame","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Braham  .","German (also <b>Bräme</b>): variant of   Brahm   2. The surnames <i>Brame</i> and <i>Bräme</i> are very rare in Germany.","French: nickname from Old Occitan <i>brame</i> ‘cry, howl’."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Braham was born in 1343, in Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Braham Jr, was -6 and her mother, Mrs. Joan De Braham, was -11. She had at least 2 daughters with Robert de Bucton. She died before 1408."},"et":{"1343–BEF 1408":"1343–enne 1408","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1341–1408":"1341–1408","1377–1427":"1377–1427","1393–Female":"1393–Surnud","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1355–1432":"1355–1432","BEF 1408":"enne 1408","about 1393":"umbes 1393","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1377":"1377","1432":"1432","1355":"1355","1343":"1343","1420":"14